[[Category:Fan Roles]] [[Category:Variable Team Roles]] [[Category:Stubs]]

{| class="wikitable" style="float:right; margin-left: 10px;" |-}
== Description == * View someone likely to be alive by the time you plan to reveal as [[Seer]], or at least who will be alive next day, otherwise your view is wasted. This is impossible to know, but think of likely [[Werewolf]] targets: ** Players who everyone trusts, not likely to be killed during the day, are likely to be killed at night ** Players who have "proven" that they are a special role that is a threat to wolves are likely to be killed at night ** Players who are considered skill [[Werewolf]] hunters, who are good at figuring out who the wolves are and have a history for getting killed at night early on are likely to be killed at night * Prepare for a [[Whisper Campaign]] ** View your neighbors. Even if there are roles, such as [[Sorcerer]], [[Wolf Man]], or [[Cursed]] that might undermine the campaign, since once those roles are known to be dead the information becomes useful. ** View neighbors of those who die at night. Wolves are more threatened by their neighbors and are more likely to kill them if they can be viewed by the [[Seer]] and there is a possibility of a [[Whisper Campaign]]. * View someone with many strong opinions, so if they are a wolf you can make inferences about who they tried to kill and who they tried to protect. ** Note that werewolves will protect innocent people and will vote to kill wolves, especially when they think their nomination or vote won't matter. * Choose from a pool that is more likely to contain werewolves ** If a werewolf is killed, and it was clear that most if not everyone would vote to kill, then those who vote to save are often more likely to be villagers. Rather than stand out as the one who voted to save a wolf, a wolf would rather hide in the majority vote and earning the "I voted to kill a wolf" badge that they can use in their defense for the rest of the game. Beginners may be exceptions thinking they have to protect their partners. ** It is not likely that early on, in a village without expendable werewolves, that a werewolf will go after their partner when there is a real risk they will die. So if the village kills a wolf, view someone other than the person who nominated or seconded them, or who provided evidence against them that turned the vote against them. * When you find a wolf, don't announce it right away. Spend the day observing the known wolf and see if you can make inferences about who might be their partner and who is likely not their partner. * View people who are hard to read. * View people who aren't being helpful, who are wasting time, causing confusion and chaos, refuse to speak or offer opinions, or undermine the whisper campaign. * View people who are not focused and paying attention, e.g. playing with cell phone. Werewolves don't need info because they have all the info they need.
